description.text:
These are smooth, slip-on vise pads that are easily adjustable in OpenSCAD. If you don't want jaw marks imprinted on your work piece, these pads will protect your work.

These pads slip around the entire jaw of your vise so they don't easily fall off during use.

To adjust these pads for your bench vise's jaw dimensions, change viseX, viseY, and viseZ parameters (please refer diagrams above). Increase your measurements by 1% to account for ABS shrinkage.

The thickness of the top, bottom, sides, and face are adjustable in millimeters.

Printer:

no-name i3 clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

To reduce warping, I recommend using a 10mm brim and setting "overhang" in the openSCAD script to your minimum value.

These pads are very good under compression. If you intend to use very high pressure on your vise while using these pads, print at 30% infill, 1.6mm walls, and 1.6mm top/bottom thickness and I will be surprised if you can crack these pads by hand.

In the script, you can increase your vise dimensions by a percentage to account for shrinkage. I recommend adding 1% to your jaw dimensions when printing with ABS. Using 1%, I am able to slip these pads on and off by hand with no slop.

Note: To see the difference overhang has on warping, see post-printing instructions on http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1933068.

Cracking

Sometimes you will get cracking above the face of the pad where the print goes from a solid face to hollow. The cracking will occur after cooling has finished. I recommend completely separating the crack and then gluing the two pieces together again (as shown in the pictures above).

So far in my printing experience, hot-melt glue is the best for gluing ABS back together again.

The pads are still very strong under compression.

OpenSCAD

I designed these using OpenSCAD. You may or may not have tried it before, but it is stupid-simple to adjust these pads for your printer (just input a few parameters into the top of the script).

description.text:
I saw everyone was making these fidget spinners. I made one that used all bearings. I also saw some that had hex nuts in them. I didn't have any hex nuts but I had pennies. I went to tinkercad and created one.

These are a bit smaller than the normal ones that use just 22mm bearings, which if you have kids, make it easier for them to spin them.

Edit: I noticed that the outer rings are off a bit. I will work on getting this corrected and upload a better version :)

Edit#2 11/20/2016: Updated newer fixed stl. Enjoy!

Edit#3: Added 6 sided spinner!

Monoprice Maker Select V2.1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

50

Notes:

In tinkercad I had used a lucky penny holder and extended the top and bottom lips so that the pennies do not fall out. This possibly lead to some stringing on the top layers that would need to be cleaned up before pushing the pennies in. This can probably be solved by making the lip smaller.. I just wanted to make it to where the pennies dont fall out.

You could probably print this with PLA and insert the pennies as the nozzle moves to the appropriate height, but printing it with TPU or any flexible filament would make it easier to wait until the end to pop them in. When they get in there, it is very hard to get them out.

The advantage of this type is that you don't have to fiddle around with a shaft through the centre, you can just sit the spool right on top. Other hardware required for this:
  • 4 scooter/skateboard bearings
  • PVC pressure pipe with a ID of 17.5 mm. (DN 15 / NPS 1/2)
    • UPDATE:
    Version 2 can be found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:204244

• Print out the parts.
  • Press the scooter bearings into the adapters. They won't go all the way in, I have designed it so that they stick out 1 mm (so the adapter doesn't rub against the chassis).
  • Cut off 105 mm of pipe * 2.
  • Put the adapters on the end of the pipe.
  • Put the rollers onto the chassis. You may need to shorten the pipes a little so that they just fit snug.

title: 40 mm hotend fan duct and bracket

description.text:
I needed a fan for my hotend and had left the matter for too long. I had started to get really bad prints due to heat creeping up the hotend and clogging the filament feed. This is a quick and dirty 40 mm fan duct with bracket for my prusa.
The bracket only has (3mm) screw holes on one edge since my x-carriage doesn't have any mounting brackets. This will have to be glued in place. Since I really was suffering with my prints, this part came out badly and required fixing. This is due to the filament not feeding properly because it jams in the hot hotend. I'll post pictures later though. Upcoming:
Nozzle extension from duct to the hotend to direct the full airflow to the hotend. Adapter for 60 mm (or whatever I have at home) fan.
This exist now: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:192742 I consider (in hindsight admittedly) the hotend fan to be a part of a 3d printer since without it the heat will creep and filament will clog so this is filed under 3d Printer Parts Pics uploaded. As you can see, I had issues with the print quality and fixed with masking tape. The bracket has an indentation for a nut on the outside but since the screws I used were too long (25mm) they would interfere with the assembly onto the x-carriage. This is why I have the bolt head on the side of the bracket in the two last pictures.

I made a cylindrical piston before which came out great except for a few leaks. So one day i got the idea of trying out another shape starting with a rectangular piston. I designed the walls to be a lot thicker in case the corners ever became critical points if the piston were to start storing pressure. The print was coming out great until I heard a loud pop from my makerbot. Upon further inspection, I found my idler wheel had snapped. Fortunately, I have a spare idler wheel and hopefully will only be out of commission for a day.

I had my skeinforge set to fill at .7 which proved to be a bit too much. At some point the plastic began to bulge out and i needed to use a tweezer to smooth it out. I would say .5 would be a good number to avoid leaks without too much overlapping and bulging.

title: TEVO Tarantula - Motherboard and LCD boxes
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
TEVO Tarantula - Motherboard and LCD boxes

I spent endless nights on that design. I couldn't believe it would be so tricky to draw "boxes".
I've printed small portions of each box to test the different features (M3-nut holes, fan housing. I publish everything as I'm pretty confident of the result but I must admit I did not print everything.

Description

The rear box contains the Makerbase motherboard : either MKS_GEN or MKS_BASE will fit in it. This box is fixed on the top V-slot with T-nuts/bolts
The front box contains the LCD screen.

Quick and dirty installation guide :

  • You'll need a bunch of M3 nuts, 8 & 12mm M3 bolts, M3-25mm long brass nuts.
  • You'll also need 2 fans : 40x40x10 - 12V (Alseye ones are perfect, silent and cheap)

Assembly hardware :

Mount MKS Base : 4x M3 10mm bolts + 4x M3 nuts
Mount MKS Gen : 4x M3 10 or 12mm bolts + 4x M3 nuts
Assemble The MKS Box : 4x M3 25mm brass nuts + 8x M3 10 or 12mm bolts
Assemble the LCD box : 4x M3 20mm bolts + 4x M3 nuts

2 or 3x M4 T-Nuts + M4 10mm bolts

Note : LCD screens are made of 2 parts that are often very badly soldered. You may find that holes are not coinciding well. Don't worry, you don't even need to fix the LCD screen in the box

Assembly Notes :

  • Print the 4 parts
  • Insert M3 nuts in the corresponding holes, insert 25mm long brass nut that will fix both parts of the MKS box
  • Mount MKS_front box on top v-slot
  • Mount LCD_rear on MKS_front part
  • Slide the 2 fans in their housing. Ensure airflow is unidirectional. You should not need any screw.
  • Assemble both motherboard and LCD screen, wire them together.
  • Mount top parts, use M3 bolts (optional as the boxes should be self sealed)

Note : Do not hesitate to leave me a little tip if you like the design. That helps me to pay the filament I waste when I print prototypes.

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3 mm layer

Infill:

30-40%

Notes:

DO NOT USE SUPPORT.
The design is especially done to avoid the usage of support. If you add support, they may be hard to remove.

description.text:
This is a printable Formlabs Form1+ printable vat. I got tired of having to buy a $50 vat every time the PDMS wore out, so I designed this so I could make my own. I attempted to replace the PDMS in the existing commercial vats, but the acrylic frame was already cracked from repeated use which made it impossible.

I printed this with 3-4 perimeters, 0.2mm layer height, 50% infill out of PLA.

DO NOT USE ABS AS IT WILL MELT WITH REPEATED UV RESIN EXPOSURE.

For V1, add a 1/4" x 5.75" x 6" piece of glass. For V2 (with the pour lip), add a 6mm x 160mm x 150mm piece of glass. Epoxy it in place and then add 65g Sylgard 184 PDMS. Make sure when you pour it that it's completely level! Also: you may have to fine tune your Z-height, so please check this when using this vat!

V1 is very similar in appearance to the stock Form1+ vat. V2 has the tabs removed and the exposure window spans the entire length of the vat. With the tabs removed, you can rotate the vat 180° if you prefer to print on one particular side of the build platform.

I have printed about two-dozen parts on this vat design and have to say it works REALLY well.
Designed in Autodesk Inventor 2016.

Print in Ninjaflex for a durable toy that works well for bath time too. For the print in the photo, I split the part in two halves and used a hot knife to remove support material on the fins and antenna. Heat a thin metal spatula over a candle and slide it between the two halves to fuse them together. Glue doesn't work very well on Ninjaflex.

I printed mine half-size in white and colored with permanent markers... the red came out pink, but my kiddo still loves it. I'd recommend using red filament as a base instead if you want it to look like Rocket from the cartoon.

title: Stars for Christmas Decoration - LED light

description.text:
This Christmas decoration star is illuminated with an LED strip.

I designed it to have a nice advent decoration with functions also as an ambience light.

Some details about the designing process you can explore in my video. (German language)
https://youtu.be/e-ejxozyQkI

I provide also DIY-Kits with already printed stars and the proper LED-stripe:
http://ewap.ch/produkt/stern-als-adventsdekoration/

See the video form ScienceMadeFunner. He made a video as he printed this thing. His modification is wonderful. https://youtu.be/lkWRz-czdd0

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

The parts are designed to print with a extrusion width of 0.4mm. Why this is important i explain in the video. But for short, it is because of the vertical wall thickness is 0.8mm.
Some slicers like Sli3r need a extrusion width settings of 0.44mm to get perimeters with 0.4mm width.

The Stars you have to print. Then you need some 10mm wide and 74mm long LED-stripes. For isolation some shrink tubing is recommended. DIY-Kit

All the Items from the Picture above you can order from me.
http://ewap.ch/produkt/stern-als-adventsdekoration/

If you just need the LED stripe you can order it on Amazon:
http://amzn.to/2fjGaPn

You also need some wire, an 12V power adapter (500mA for 4 stars) and the tools you see.

Main design features

I like to bring up the following design features:

  • The Wall thickness is optimized to give a uniform light distribution
  • The two half of the star mount without any additional connecting element
  • There are two ways to mount the star (#1 to a 5mm rod or #2 to a wall) in both ways the groove has his function!
  • The LED stripe form-fit to his position. Because glue will not hold enough over time.

Again you can watch my YouTube Video where i explain it in German.

Bad light distribution with the wrong wall thickness. Good light distribution when the extrusion width matches 0.5x the horizontal wall thickness.

title: Da Vinci 1.0a windows: Screen or clear

description.text:
My printer came without the plastic oval windows. This project has two options. The first is a one-piece netted window to keep bugs out. The other option is a no-net window, plus a shim, that you can use to attach a piece of clear acrylic.

This is pretty heavily parametrizable if you want to use it in a different project/printer.

In the OpenSCAD file, set net_thickness=0 to print a window, and set only_shim=true to print the shim for holding the acrylic in place.

Printer:

XYZ DaVinci 1.0a with Repetier

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.35

Infill:

20%

Notes:

With the default settings, print at exactly 0.35 layer in ABS. (You could try to customize the layer_height and net_thickness parameters if you want a different size.)

For the net, make sure your bed adhesion isn't very strong, or you'll break the net when you pry it off. A worn purple glue stick coating worked well for me, except that some of the verticals ended up crooked--but it's still functional.

You can cut 1/16" acrylic easily with tin snips.

title: Rigidbot Titan extruder mount w/ Volcano hotend

description.text:
I couldn't find a suitable extruder mount to use the E3d titan extruder with the V6 and volcano hotend. So I just made one. This mount comes equipped with everything you will ever need for your hotend. It comes with Z-sensor probe mount, Cooling fan mount, halo light mount for hotend and layer cooling fan mount. I recommend printing everything in ABS or better.

There is a rectangle piece that is for the belt connector. I left it by itself because depending on what you use to connect your belt you may need it.

Its one big file with all the models inside but i recommend you print the parts one at a time. The models are in the best orientation for printing. The cooling fan is very snug but it works and stays in place perfectly. The layer cooling fan may need to be shaved down by its snap connectors.The screws needed for the layer cooling fan are m3 x 16mm. The light is held in place by 2 small zip ties, The screws needed are the same ones found on the printer. I salvaged them from various parts of the printer. The 4 screws that hold the motor to the platform come from the old bearing mount along with the 2 screws that hold the light in place. The 2 screws that hold the z-probe come from the plastic panel on the side of the frame. The screws that hold the 40 mm fan come from the original extruder i believe.

For the z-sensor probe i changed the offset code to this
define X_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER 11
define Y_PROBE_OFFSET_FROM_EXTRUDER -44
This is fairly close and is a good starting point should you want to adjust.

Also changed the 4 probing sections
define LEFT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 50
define RIGHT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 190
define BACK_PROBE_BED_POSITION 170
define FRONT_PROBE_BED_POSITION 50

I remixed from these other models
Cooling fan
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:988310

Extruder/hotend mount
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1522911

bearing mounts
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:430288

The platform supports this adjustable belt connector
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:793499

This is the halo light i used
https://www.superbrightleds.com/moreinfo/led-headlight-accent-lights/led-angel-eye-headlight-accent-lights-cob/2797/
Part number: AE60-CWCOB
Color: Cool White

Final word: Yes i know it takes away from some of the Z print area but how often are you printing all the way to the top? As with most models this is still a work in progress but functional. As far as the wires go i just zip tied them around the motor.

UPDATE #1 - Updated the layer cooling model. its less of a hack job and more of a solid piece. It was also shortened a bit and angled. The clips on it were also spaced a bit more too.

Update #2 - The z sensor probe mount has been updated. You just have to reprint the z sensor mount not anything else. The first one was a little flimsy. Print with support and 100% infill. Use longer screws to hold it in place. Its very snug, and meant to be, when putting in place.

Update #3 - I revamped the whole design and made it more modular with everything fitting better. The redesign was for easier assembly and disassembly, better fit with parts and simpler design. There are are a few more screws needed for this as well. However I have yet to try and print it so use at your own risk. The new experimental .stl is called X2
